05998nam a22008775i 9780823290680DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232906807 a10.1515/97808232906802doi  a(DE-B1597)571331  a(OCoLC)1224279249  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0270002bisacsh04a1942231 aDerrida, Jacques, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDeconstruction in a Nutshell :bA Conversation with Jacques Derrida, With a New Introduction /cJacques Derrida; ed. by John D. Caputo. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction (2020) Specters of Derrida -- tPART ONE The Villanova Roundtable A Conversation with Jacques Derrida -- tThe Villanova Roundtable A Conversation with Jacques Derrida. EDITORIAL NOTE -- tPART TWO A Commentary: Deconstruction In a Nutshell -- t1. Deconstruction in a Nutshell: The Very Idea (!) -- t2. The Right to Philosophy -- t3. Khôra: Being Serious with Plato -- t4. Community Without Community -- t5. Justice, If Such a Thing Exists -- t6. The Messianic: Waiting for the Future -- t7. Re-Joyce, Say "Yes" -- tA Concluding Amen -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume, consisting of a conversation with Derrida that is further elaborated by one of his leading interpreters, represents one of the most lucid, compact and reliable introductions to Derrida and deconstruction available in any language. A substantial new Introduction traces the development of deconstruction alongside other philosophical movements since Derrida’s death.Responding to questions put to him at a roundtable held at Villanova University in 1994, Jacques Derrida leads the reader through an illuminating discussion of the central themes of deconstruction. Speaking in English and extemporaneously, Derrida takes up with unusual clarity and great eloquence such topics as the task of philosophy, the Greeks, justice, responsibility, the gift, community, and the messianic. Derrida refutes the charges of relativism that are often leveled at deconstruction by its critics and sets forth the profoundly affirmative and ethico-political thrust of his work.The roundtable is marked by an unusual clarity that continues into the second part of the book, in which one of Derrida’s most influential readers, John D. Caputo, elaborates upon Derrida’s comments and supplies material for further discussion. This edition also includes a substantial new Introduction by Caputo that discusses the original context of the book and traces the development of deconstruction since Derrida’s death in 2004, from the rise of new materialisms to return to religion.Long one of the most lucid and reliable introductions to Derrida and deconstruction available in any language, and an ideal volume for students, Deconstruction in a Nutshell will also prove illuminating for those already familiar with Derrida’s work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aReligion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh  aDerrida.  aJames Joyce.  acommunity without community.  adeconstruction.  ahospitality.  ajustice.  akhora.  amessianicity.  areligion without religion.1 aCaputo, John D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaputo, John D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE CO